\f1\b\fs32 \cf2 \page 3.0  EXECUTABLE STATEMENTS\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs22 \cf2 \
Executable  statements  operate on the data defined in the declaration statements. We think of executable  statements  as  "doing things" or manipulating objects.  Formally, executable statements are those PROTEL statements which cause sequences of machine language instructions to be generated.\
 \
Executable statements can be divided into two basic categories:\
 \
\pard\tx20\tx360\pardeftab720\li360\fi-360\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0\cf2 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone {\listtext	1.	}\up0 \nosupersub \ulnone Expressions;\
\ls7\ilvl0\up0 \nosupersub \ulnone {\listtext	2.	}\up0 \nosupersub \ulnone Control Statements.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2  \
 \
 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs32 \cf2 3.1  EXPRESSIONS\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs22 \cf2 \
\
  
\f1\b EXAMPLES
\f0\b0 \
 \
    1.  i * result -> result;\
 \
    2.  get_idle_trunk ();\
 \
Expressions  are executable statements which create new data values from existing ones.  Expressions can be categorized by  those which evaluate to a value, and those which do not.  An expression which  does  not evaluate to a value is a procedure call.  An expression is a statement if it is either an assignment  statement, or a procedure call.\
\
The assignment operator in PROTEL is "->".(2)  \
\
The  value  of  the expression\
 \
       23 -> x\
 \
is 23.\
 \
To  see  that  an assignment statement is an expression, one must understand that the assignment  operator  is  a  binary  operator which causes a side-effect.\
\
Consider the following assignment statement:\
 \
       23 + 1 -> x / 2 -> y;\
 \
  ----------------\
  2   '->'  is  pronounced  "guzinta", a derivative of "goes into".  Thus a -> b reads "a goes into b".\
 \
 \
\page Evaluation  of  arithmetic  operators in PROTEL is left-to-right.  The value of "23 + 1 -> x" is 24, with the side-effect that x has been assigned the value 24. 24 / 2  is  then  evaluated  and  the right-most  assignment operator is evaluated, causing y to be assigned the value 12. The order of evaluation of operators in this example is +, ->, /, ->.\
 \
Assignment expressions contain the assignment operator in the expression.   However, an assignment expression is a statement only if the assignment operator is the last evaluated operator in  the expression.\
 \
  
\f1\b EXAMPLES
\f0\b0 \
 \
    3.   i + 1 -> i;       % legal assignment statement.\
 \
    4.   (i + 1 -> i);     % legal assignment statement.\
 \
    5.   (i -> i + 1);     % not legal; -> not the last operator.\
 \
    6.   p(i + 1 -> i);    % legal if p does not return a value.\
 \
Procedure  calls  may be used either by themselves or as a component of an assignment statement.  When used as part of an assignment statement, a  procedure  must  have  been  declared  with  a RETURNS  clause, indicating the type of the value to be returned.  When used by itself the procedure must have been defined  without the  RETURNS clause.   A procedure call consists of the procedure name followed by the  procedure  parameters  enclosed  in  parentheses.\
 \
In  example 1 above, the value of i is multiplied by the value of result and the new value assigned to result.\
 \
In example 2 the procedure get_idle_trunk is called.   Note  that this  procedure  has  no  parameters as is indicated by the empty parentheses.\
 \
The basic components of an \ul expression\ulnone   are  \ul operators\ulnone ,  \ul operands\ulnone , and \ul parentheses\ulnone .\
\
The operands and operators are indicated in the statement in Figure 5.\
 \
 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

